					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12845566#post-4439740</guid>
				<title>Junior Staff - SIte Crit</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12845566/scp-4492#post-4439740</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Fri, 06 Dec 2019 15:34:24 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>DrAkimoto</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>5255688</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <div class="collapsible-block"> <div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Crit/Opinion</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none"> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Bye-Bye</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-content"> <p>Okay Ellie lets see what you got,</p> <p><strong>Nitpicks:</strong></p> <blockquote> <p>SCP-4492 is to be contained in a standard object storage locker.</p> </blockquote> <p>So there is nothing adherently wrong with these containment procedures. But while it's important to always aim for conciseness when writing containment procedures I feel this is a missed opportunity. I view con procs as the first opportunity to peak interest and add a hook to get through the typically dry section. While this is technically all that is necessary for containment a line like (Testing of SCP-4492 is approved for personnel level 2/4492 and above. Testing is to be enacted in outdoor testing area 5 portable restroom and a full meal must be consumed approximately 1 hour before testing.) Now obviously not this exact thing because its just off the top of my head, but I feel something like this would definitely spice up your conprocs.</p> <blockquote> <p>After a brief testing of SCP-4492's properties,</p> </blockquote> <p>I'd cut &quot;a&quot; from before brief, but in all honesty, I think &quot;initial&quot; could work even better here.</p> <p><strong>Opinion:</strong> YOUR FIRST SCIP! Despite my comment on the containment procedures this is very well done, as expected. The information provided is clear and concise and no time is wasted getting to the gem of this article, the dialogue. Usually in a short article like this one specific section carries the piece and the dialogue here does that in abundance, it's well written and believable. An easy +1 from me and I hope to see more scips from you in the future.</p> </div> </div> </div> <br /> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">&#32;</span><br /> Site crit : <span style="font-size:smaller;"><strong>Disclaimer:</strong> <em>Opinions expressed in this review do not reflect the opinions of SCP Wiki staff as a whole. Please respond to <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/drakimoto" ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=5255688&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1575646483" alt="DrAkimoto" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=5255688)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/drakimoto" >DrAkimoto</a></span> or contact the captain of the Site Criticism Team, <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/soullesssingularity" ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=637830&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1575646483" alt="SoullessSingularity" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=637830)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/soullesssingularity" >SoullessSingularity</a></span>, for any questions or concerns relating to this review.</em></span>
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
